Gene Wolfe stories are funny, because if you "solve" them during the first reading, it was actually a false solution that Wolfe intended the reader to fall for. It's like the Japanese setting up a false spy ring for the Allies to discover and a deep spy ring no one even suspects.

Also Gene Wolfe plots are basically resistant to summaries and any "plot summary" has to use a ton of "probably", "appears to", "might have", etc. because you can't be sure unless you actually solve it and the true plot is always in its gaps, details, etc. A bulletproof writer.
